nded above all on the intense study and – in the case of music – practice of artistic technique. The essays in this volume explore Mansfield’s relationships with the visual arts and with music, bringing to light the way in which these helped to shape the formal qualities of her writing: its beauty of line and intensely musical effects. Mansfield’s relationship with Woolf is also strongly in the frame. As befits a volume dedicated to the arts, there is an introduction, poetry and a new short story by highly-acclaimed writers who count Mansfield amongst their chief inspirations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aArt and literature. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aAdcock, Fleur, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBinckes, Faith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBowler, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFraser, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGirl, Colonial, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGunn, Kirsty, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarding, Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarrison, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKaplan, Sydney Janet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarl, Alissa G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKemp, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKennedy, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKimber, Gerri, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aKimber, Gerri, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocab